## 4 Verifiably Robust Conformal Prediction (VRCP)

In this section, we formally introduce two variants of VRCP. Both methods allow us to construct adversarially robust prediction sets at inference time.

The first variant, _VRCP via Robust Inference (VRCP-I)_, employs NN verification at inference time to compute a lower bound of the score for the given test input (best-case score), thereby obtaining more conservative regions. The calibration procedure is computed as in standard CP. The second variant, _VRCP via Robust Calibration (VRCP-C)_, instead uses NN verification at calibration time to derive upper bounds for the calibration scores (worst-case), thereby obtaining a more conservative calibration threshold (critical value). This allows us to use the regular scores at inference time, without requiring NN verification.

### Verifiably Robust Conformal Prediction via Robust Inference (VRCP-I)

Given a calibration set \(\mathcal{D}_{\text{cal}}\), a test input \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\), and score function \(S(\cdot,\cdot)\), we compute the prediction set for \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\) as follows.

1. For each \(y\in Y\) we compute, \[s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)\leq\inf_{\bm{x}^{\prime}\in B_{\epsilon}(\bm{x}_{n+1})}S( \bm{x}^{\prime},y).\] (5)
2. The robust prediction set is then defined as \[C_{\epsilon}(\bm{x}_{n+1})=\{y:s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)\leq Q_{1-\alpha}(F)\}.\] (6)

Below, we show that we are able to maintain the marginal coverage guarantee from Eq. (2) for any \(\ell_{p}\)-norm bounded adversarial attack.

**Theorem 1**.: _Let \(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1}=\bm{x}_{n+1}+\bm{\delta}\) for a clean test sample \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\) and \(\|\bm{\delta}\|_{p}\leq\epsilon\). The prediction set \(C_{\epsilon}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1})\) defined in Eq. (6) satisfies \(\mathbb{P}\left[y_{n+1}\in C_{\epsilon}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1})\right]\geq 1-\alpha\)._

Proof.: We obtain that

\[\mathbb{P}\left[y_{n+1}\in C_{\epsilon}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1})\right] =\mathbb{P}\left[s^{\perp}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1},y_{n+1})\leq Q_{1 -\alpha}(F)\right]\] \[\geq\mathbb{P}\left[\inf_{\bm{x}^{\prime}\in B_{\epsilon}(\tilde {\bm{x}}_{n+1})}S(\bm{x}^{\prime},y_{n+1})\leq Q_{1-\alpha}(F)\right]\] by Eq. (5) \[\geq\mathbb{P}\left[S(\bm{x}_{n+1},y_{n+1})\leq Q_{1-\alpha}(F) \right]\;\geq\;1-\alpha.\qed\]

### Verifiably Robust Conformal Prediction via Robust Calibration

Given a calibration set \(\mathcal{D}_{\text{cal}}\), a test input \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\), and score function \(S(\cdot,\cdot)\), we compute the robustly calibrated prediction set for \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\) as follows.

1. We compute the upper-bound calibration distribution as: \[F^{\top}=\frac{\delta_{\infty}}{(n+1)}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\delta_{s_{i}^{\top }}}{n+1}\text{, where }s_{i}^{\top}\geq\sup_{\bm{x}^{\prime}\in B_{\epsilon}(\bm{x}_{i})}S(\bm{x}^{ \prime},y_{i}).\] (7)
2. The robust post-calibration prediction set is then defined as \[C_{\epsilon}(\bm{x}_{n+1})=\{y:S(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)\leq Q_{1-\alpha}(F^{\top})\}.\] (8)

**Theorem 2**.: _Let \(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1}=\bm{x}_{n+1}+\bm{\delta}\) for a clean test sample \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\) and \(\|\bm{\delta}\|_{p}\leq\epsilon\). The prediction set \(C_{\epsilon}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1})\) defined in Eq. (8) satisfies \(\mathbb{P}\left[y_{n+1}\in C_{\epsilon}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1})\right]\geq 1-\alpha\)._

Proof.: We have that

\[\mathbb{P}\left[y_{n+1}\in C_{\epsilon}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1})\right] =\mathbb{P}\left[S(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1},y_{n+1})\leq Q_{1-\alpha }\left(F^{\top}\right)\right]\] \[\geq\mathbb{P}\left[S(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{n+1},y_{n+1})\leq Q_{1- \alpha}\left(\left\{\sup_{\bm{x}^{\prime}\in B_{\epsilon}(\bm{x}_{i})}S(\bm{x} ^{\prime},y_{i})\right\}_{i=1}^{n}\cup\{\infty\}\right)\right]\] \[\geq 1-\alpha\]

Let \(P^{\top}\) denote the distribution of \((\bm{x}^{\top},y)\) where \(\bm{x}^{\top}=\text{argsup}_{\bm{x}^{\prime}\in B_{\epsilon}(\bm{x})}S(\bm{x}^ {\prime},y)\) and \((\bm{x},y)\sim P\). The final inequality above holds since it is equivalent to constructing a CP prediction set using \(n\) i.i.d realisations of \(P^{\top}\) and evaluating it on \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\sim P^{\top}\). The resulting set will include the true test output \(y_{n+1}\) with probability at least \(1-\alpha\). 

### Computation of score bounds

ClassificationIn the classification setting, we use the score function proposed in (Lei et al., 2013; Gendler et al., 2021):

\[S(\bm{x},y)=1-f(\bm{x})_{y},\] (9)where \(f(\bm{x})_{y}\in(0,1)\) is the model-predicted likelihood for label \(y\). In this setting, to compute \(s^{\perp}\) and \(s^{\top}\) (required by VRCP-I and VRCP-C, respectively), it suffices to use NN verification algorithms to derive the output bounds for \(f(\bm{x})\). Specifically, in VRCP-I, for a test input \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\) and for each \(y\in Y\) we derive \(s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)\) as

\[s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)=1-f(\bm{x}_{n+1})_{y}^{\top},\] (10)

where \(f(\bm{x}_{n+1})_{y}^{\top}\) denotes the upper bound computed by the neural network verifier for the model-predicted likelihood of label \(y\in Y\) and input \(\bm{x}_{n+1}\).

In VRCP-C, for each calibration point \((\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})\) we compute \(s^{\top}(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})\) as

\[s^{\top}(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})=1-f(\bm{x}_{i})_{y_{i}}^{\perp},\] (11)

where \(f(\bm{x}_{i})_{y_{i}}^{\perp}\) denotes the lower bound of the model output for label \(y_{i}\) given input \(\bm{x}_{i}\).

RegressionIn the regression tasks, we follow the conformalized quantile regression (CQR) methodology proposed by (Romano et al., 2019). We train quantile regressors \(f_{\alpha_{\text{low}}}\) and \(f_{\alpha_{\text{high}}}\) to estimate the \(\alpha_{\text{low}}=\alpha/2\) and \(\alpha_{\text{high}}=1-\alpha/2\) quantiles of \(y\mid\bm{x}\). In CQR, we use the following score function:

\[S(\bm{x},y)=\max\left\{f_{\alpha_{\text{low}}}(\bm{x})-y,y-f_{\alpha_{\text{ high}}}(\bm{x})\right\}.\] (12)

Unlike classification, where the label space is discrete, we cannot construct the region explicitly by enumerating all possible outputs \(y\). Instead, the prediction region for a given test point \(C(\bm{x}_{n+1})\) is constructed implicitly, by adjusting the quantile predictions by the critical value of the calibration distribution \(Q_{1-\alpha}(F)\), as follows:

\[C(\bm{x}_{n+1})=\left[f_{\alpha_{\text{low}}}(\bm{x}_{n+1})-Q_{1-\alpha}(F),f _{\alpha_{\text{high}}}(\bm{x}_{n+1})+Q_{1-\alpha}(F)\right]\] (13)

In both VRCP-C and VRCP-I, the score function leverages an NN verifier to derive the bounds over the upper and lower quantiles of the model. In VRCP-C, we compute the worst-case calibration scores as:

\[s^{\top}(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})=\max\left\{f_{\alpha_{\text{low}}}^{\top}(\bm{x}_ {i})-y_{i},y_{i}-f_{\alpha_{\text{high}}}^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{i})\right\}.\] (14)

In VRCP-I for classification, for each output we check inclusion in \(C_{\epsilon}\) by using the best-case score \(s^{\perp}\). As explained above, explicit enumeration is infeasible for regression, and so we construct our robust region by replacing predicted quantiles in Eq. (13) with their conservative approximations, as follows:

\[C_{\epsilon}(\bm{x}_{n+1})=\left[f_{\alpha_{\text{low}}}^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1}) -Q_{1-\alpha}(F),f_{\alpha_{\text{high}}}^{\top}(\bm{x}_{n+1})+Q_{1-\alpha}(F )\right]\] (15)

The above-defined region is equivalent to enumerating all possible outputs \(y\), and for each, considering the best-case score \(s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)=\max\left\{f_{\alpha_{\text{low}}}^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n +1})-y,y-f_{\alpha_{\text{high}}}^{\top}(\bm{x}_{n+1})\right\}\). A proof is available in Appendix A.

A nice property of both VRCP-I and VRCP-C is that they guarantee that they can only increase the size of the prediction set for any input \(\bm{x}\) compared to vanilla CP, thus will always attain at least as much coverage as the vanilla CP procedure. Moreover, as we show in Section 5, both algorithms do not trivially inflate the size of the prediction sets and maintain a similar distribution of set sizes. This is formalised in the Proposition 1, which is proved in Appendix A.

**Proposition 1**.: _Let \(C(\bm{x})\) and \(C_{\epsilon}(\bm{x})\) be the prediction sets obtained using vanilla CP and VRCP (using VRCP-I or VRCP-C), respectively. For any input \(\bm{x}\), we have that \(C(\bm{x})\subseteq C_{\epsilon}(\bm{x})\)._

## 5 Evaluation

We evaluate VRCP-I and VRCP-C on classification (image) and regression (RL) benchmarks, and compare them against the SotA approaches on each benchmark. For all the networks used, we did not perform adversarial training as we assume that the attack budget \(\epsilon\) is unknown at training time. Nonetheless, both our approaches can benefit from adversarial training, as it results in models that are more verifiable and have tighter bounds for the same attack budget.3

