2. \(s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)=y-f^{\top}\), which implies that \(y\in[\frac{f^{\top}+f^{\perp}}{2},f^{\top}+q]\). It suffices to show that \(y-f^{\top}\leq q\) for \(y=f^{\top}+q\), which is clearly satisfied.

Finally, we show that \(y\not\in C_{\epsilon}(\bm{x}_{n+1})\) implies \(s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)>q\): if \(y<f^{\perp}-q\), we have that \(s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)=f^{\perp}-y>q\). Similarly, if \(y>f^{\perp}+q\), we have that \(s^{\perp}(\bm{x}_{n+1},y)=y-f^{\top}>q\). 

